:"1279","1245":"1245","1275":"1275","1296":"1296.","1340":"1340","1272":"1272","about 1275":"oko 1275.","1270":"1270","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"cs":{"about 1275–1305":"okolo 1275–1305","1270–Male":"1270–Zesnulý","1272–Male":"1272–Zesnulý","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1279–1340":"1279–1340","1305–1337":"1305–1337","1245–Male":"1245–Zesnulý","1247–Female":"1247–Zesnulá","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1340":"1340","1272":"1272","about 1275":"okolo 1275","1270":"1270","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"da":{"about 1275–1305":"omkring 1275–1305","1270–Male":"1270–Afdød","1272–Male":"1272–Afdød","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1279–1340":"1279–1340","1305–1337":"1305–1337","1245–Male":"1245–Afdød","1247–Female":"1247–Afdød","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1340":"1340","1272":"1272","about 1275":"omkring 1275","1270":"1270","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"nl":{"about 1275–1305":"circa 1275–1305","1270–Male":"1270–Overleden","1272–Male":"1272–Overleden","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1279–1340":"1279–1340","1305–1337":"1305–1337","1245–Male":"1245–Overleden","1247–Female":"1247–Overleden","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1340":"1340","1272":"1272","about 1275":"circa 1275","1270":"1270","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1275–1305":"about 1275–1305","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1272–Male":"1272–Deceased","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1279–1340":"1279–1340","1305–1337":"1305–1337","1245–Male":"1245–Deceased","1247–Female":"1247–Deceased","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1340":"1340","1272":"1272","about 1275":"about 1275","1270":"1270","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ab","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Turkish: ornamental name or nickname from <i>ay</i> ‘Moon’, by extension also ‘beautiful face’.","Hungarian (<b>Áy</b>): unexplained.","Chinese: alternative Mandarin form of the surname 艾, see   Ai   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ai","meanings":["Japanese: usually written 阿井 with characters used phonetically. The meaning could be ‘meeting’. In North America, it may also be a shortened form of some other name.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 艾, referring to ‘Chinese mugwort’, a type of plant used in traditional Chinese medical treatment: (i) perhaps from the second element of Ru Ai (汝艾), the name of an official who lived during the reign of Shao Kang, the 6th king of the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). (ii) from the first element of the placename Ai Ling (艾陵), the name of a hill (located in Shandong province), the fief of Ai Kong (艾孔), an official in the state of Qi during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) from the placename Ai (艾), the name of a fief (located in Jiangxi province) which was granted to an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iv) adopted as a surname by the Qu Jin (去斤), Qu Ai (去艾), and Ai Jin (艾斤) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (v) from Ai (艾), the name of an ancient state (possibly in present-day Jiangxi province) during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 愛, meaning ‘love’ in Chinese: (i) said to be traced back to Ai Xie Wu (愛邪勿), prime minister of the state of Huihu (known as Uyghur Empire or Uyghur Khaganate), who was endowed with the surname Ai (愛) by Emperor Wuzong of Tang (814–846  AD ). (ii) a Han Chinese surname for some members of the Aisin Gioro family from the Manchu ethnic group, known as the royal family of the Qing dynasty (1616 – 1911  AD ). (iii) a surname from minority ethnic groups in Taiwan."]}]},{"name":"Ifor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: (i) relationship name from Old Scandinavian  <i>Ívarr</i>,  <i>Iwar</i>,  <i>Ivar</i> ‘yew-army’. (ii) relationship name, possibly from the Welsh male given name  <i>Ifor</i>; if so, it is not clear that it survives today."],"variants":[{"name":"Ivers","meanings":["Irish: from <b>Ó hÍomhair</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Íomhar</i>’, a Gaelic form of the Old Norse personal name <i>Ívarr</i> (see   Iverson   2), with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. It is occasionally Anglicized as   Howard  . Also a shortened form of <b>Mac Íomhair</b> ‘son of <i>Íomhar</i>’, with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. See   McIver  .","North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Ivar</i> (see   Iversen  ).","English: variant of <b>Iver</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, a habitational name from Iver (Buckinghamshire) named from Old English <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place called with the same word."]},{"name":"Iver","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Iver (Bucks) named from Old English * <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place named with the same word.","2  Scottish: (i) relationship name, reduced form of Irish and Scottish Gaelic  <b>Mac Íomhair</b>,  see  McIvor  . (ii) relationship name from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Ivar</i>;  see  Ivor  ."]},{"name":"Iverson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Iver, Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Selmer, Thor, Evald, Gunner, Helmer, Ingman, Jarl, Joneen.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Iversen   and of Swedish <b>Ivarsson</b> (see   Ivarson  ), all cognates of 2 below.","English (Kent and London): patronymic from Old Norse <i>Ívarr</i>, <i>Iwar</i>, <i>Ivar</i>, a compound of either <i>ív</i> ‘yew tree, bow’ or <i>Ing</i> (the name of a god) + <i>ar</i> ‘warrior’ or ‘spear’. Alternatively, the name might be a patronymic from the Welsh male personal name <i>Ifor</i>, itself from British Celtic <i>Iūdomāros</i> ‘lord’ + ‘great’, but if so, it is not clear that it survives today."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Philip ab Ifor Lord of Iscoed was born about 1275, in Wales, his father, Ivor Marshall ap Meyric, was 31 and his mother, ferch Philip, was 30. He married Catherine ferch Llywelyn Ap Griffith in 1296. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1305, in Wales, at the age of 31."},"et":{"about 1275–1305":"umbes 1275–1305","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1279–1340":"1279–1340","1305–1337":"1305–1337","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1247–Female":"1247–Surnud","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1340":"1340","1272":"1272","about 1275":"umbes 1275","1270":"1270","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1275–1305":"noin 1275–1305","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1272–Male":"1272–Kuollut","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1279–1340":"1279–1340","1305–1337":"1305–1337","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1247–Female":"1247–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1340":"1340","1